# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1921-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1921-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1921-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1921-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1921-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1921-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1921-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1921-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1921-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1921-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1921-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1921-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1921-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1921-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The **1921 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1921 season.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The 18th edition of the World Series, it matched the National League (NL) champion New York Giants and the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The Series matched two distinct teams in strategy with the Giants, dedicated practitioners of the dead-ball era's "inside game" and the Yankees, who relied on the "power game" exemplified by Babe Ruth, who was coming off of what was arguably his best year ever statistically.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] This was the first World Series appearance by the Yankees, who have gone on to play in the Series a record 41 times.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The 1921 Series was a closely contested matchup that ended on a double play featuring a baserunning miscue.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] It was also the last of four World Series to use the best-of-nine format, which had been used in the 1903, 1919, and the 1920 editions.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The following year, the World Series permanently switched to a best-of-seven game format where it has remained ever since.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] It was also the first World Series to be broadcast over radio.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The Series was the last of the experimental best-five-of-nine series, which the Giants won five games to three.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] This marked the first time in World Series history that the series occurred at a single site.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] It happened again the following year in the same place with the same two teams, in 1944 at St.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Louis' Sportsman's Park between the Cardinals and the Browns, and then again in 2020 when the COVID-19 pandemic necessitated the first-ever neutral-site Series played at Globe Life Field in Arlington, Texas between the Los Angeles Dodgers and Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] For New Yorkers, this was the first subway Series in World Series history.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] It was also the first World Series to be broadcast on radio, with Grantland Rice covering the games live through Pittsburgh's KDKA.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] It was rebroadcast on WBZ in Massachusetts.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Announcer Tommy Cowan also recreated the games over Westinghouse-owned WJZ in Newark as he listened to phoned-in reports from the stadium.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Because of an infected arm and a bad knee (which he wrenched in Game 5), Babe Ruth did not start the final three games, appearing only as a pinch-hitter in the final inning of Game 8.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Following the Series, Ruth and Bob Meusel did some postseason barnstorming, against the rules for Series participants at that time.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Both were suspended for a number of games at the start of the 1922 season.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Ruth filed a personal appeal with Commissioner Landis, who upheld their suspensions but agreed to rescind the rule effective the end of that season.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Miller, described as "a big baseball fan" by *The New York Times*, made plans to attend games as a guest of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The Series drew fans to New York City from across the continent, from as far west as California and Mexico to as far south as Cuba.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Hotels were booked up, and both the New York Central and Pennsylvania Railroads made plans to add cars and run their trains in sections if necessary to handle the extra traffic expected.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Davis, then the Governor of Ohio, was expected to attend the games as were several other VIPs of the time.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The two were teammates on the old Baltimore Orioles in earlier seasons.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Several players on both teams didn't start the 1921 season with either the Giants or the Yankees, and several others moved to other teams during the regular season earlier that year.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] For the Giants, Johnny Rawlings, Irish Meusel, Casey Stengel and Red Causey started the season as Philadelphia Phillies, who finished last in the National League that year.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Outfielder Bill Cunningham had played for the Seattle Rainiers of the Pacific Coast League, nor did Cozy Dolan or Red Shea start the season with the Giants, while the Yankees acquired outfielder Elmer Miller and pitcher Tom Rogers during the season.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Nonparticipants from either team in the Series included Curt Walker, Lee King, Johnny Monroe, Rube Benton, Goldie Rapp, Ping Bodie, Tom Sheehan and Tom Connelly.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] This was the first of three consecutive matchups between the Yankees and Giants (1921–1923) and marked the only time (as of 2023) that three straight World Series featured the same two clubs.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Brothers Bob and Irish Meusel played against each other in each of those three series, making them the first set of brothers to play against each other on opposing teams in a World Series or any Big Four championship series.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Mays pitched a complete game 5-hit shutout, Frankie Frisch getting 4 of those hits off of Mays in a losing cause for the Giants.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] This was the first World Series game victory for the Yankees.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Pitching Ruth carefully, the Giants walked the Babe three times; but after the third walk he stole second and then third base, much to the delight of Yankee fans.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] But when he slid into third, he scraped his elbow severely and the site became infected.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Hoyt held the Giants to two hits, the Yankees jumping to a 2–0 lead in the series.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] After getting outscored 6–0 in the first two games of this series and falling behind 4–0 in the top of the third, the Giants tied it with four runs of their own in the bottom half.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Later on, an 8-run 7th inning highlighted by Ross Youngs' bases loaded triple turned the tide as the Giants got their first win of this series.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Ruth was taken out in the eighth after again scraping his elbow sliding into a base.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The Yankees announced after the game that the elbow would have to be lanced and that he would not return for the rest of the Series.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Ruth suited up, but stayed on the bench during batting practice.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] When the game began, however, to everyone's surprise, he popped out of the dugout and jogged to his outfield position.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] He kept touching his bandaged arm throughout the game.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Despite the injury, he got two hits including a ninth-inning homer, his first World Series home run as well as the first World Series home run in Yankees franchise history.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] But the Giants won the game and tied the series at 2–2.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Ruth's arm was still bandaged, but he played again.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] In the fourth, with the score tied 1–1, he shocked everyone by bunting and beating it out.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] His teammate Meusel then doubled, scoring Ruth all the way from first base for the go-ahead run in a 3–1 Yankee win.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The Giants battled back from 3–0 and 5–3 deficits to take Game 6.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Phil Douglas scattered eight hits and held the Yankees to one run, the Giants winning 2–1 on Frank Snyder's RBI double in the seventh inning.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] Facing elimination, Yankee manager Miller Huggins sent Ruth out to pinch-hit in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The Babe, nursing both elbow and knee injuries, had sat out this game and missed all of Games 6 and 7.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] The bases were empty and the Yankees still trailed by the lone run of the game scored by the Giants in the top of the first.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] A HR would tie the game, and a hit or a walk would give the Yankees a chance.
[src:1921-world-series/1921-world-series] But Ruth grounded out, and shortly afterwards Frank Baker hit into a double play after a walk by Aaron Ward who was thrown out at third base for the final out of the Series, giving the Giants their first world championship since Christy Mathewson's record three complete shutouts in 1905.
[src:1921-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1921-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
